Anonymous Sun 24 Jan 2021 00:51:06 No.35763892 Report
Quoted By:
>>35763069
Following up, a few weeks ago I explained my concept of a "living" outline to another writefag. Each story I write ends up using this framework differently, but the first completed first draft is far cleaner than pantsing things. The todo portions are often apparent once I divorce my brain from creation. And while I tend to write whole stories rather than doing dropping bits in the OP, the method stands. You'd just slice up the work into logical chunks.
Get the concept down. Might take 500 words of prose or greentext, might take 25k of a really long piece. At some point I know roughly what the start, finish, middle and other quarterly (or other major subdivision) beats are.
At that point, guess at what future scenes will be. Don't obsess. One quick sentence. Give yourself a chance to see the structure. If you're capable of storyboarding, do some here.
As you continue writing, add things to the outline. My latest has a plot summary, a few character bios, and a tangled chart of interactions. Anything that keeps you tapping keys instead of being deadlocked in thought is what you need. Since it's evolving as you write a first draft, you are documenting as you write.
If I pants a few hundred words of conversation, that's fine. Sometimes you need to let the characters yell or argue. If I start the day with five sentences which need to grow into paragraphs of exposition and narration, good.

On a day like today I should be able to quickly switch between active projects. Might take a few minutes to spin up my thoughts and resync to the outline, but I've written material for two to four wildly different stories in one day, each with their own pacing and genre.

the tl;dr - writing isn't just about getting words down. Sometimes they are random. But knowing how to catch more of your ideas is how you become a more productive writer. You're never doing your best work stressed out, and obsessing over too much or too little structure stops what matters.
